## Modifying Existing Functionality

### Rules

```
1. UNDERSTAND before changing
   - Read the existing code thoroughly
   - Understand WHY it was written this way (check git blame, commit messages, comments)
   - Identify all callers / consumers of what you're changing
   - Search for the function/component name across the entire codebase

2. MODIFY with discipline
   - Change the minimum necessary to achieve the goal
   - Don't "improve" unrelated code in the same change (separate PR)
   - If renaming within stated scope, update all callers in the same change
   - If rename/export blast radius exceeds task scope -> **ask user first**
   - If changing a function signature, update all callers in the same commit (or ask if scope is unclear)
   - Duplicate logic elsewhere -> fix task scope; **ask before** cross-file extract/refactor

3. VERIFY after changing
   - Run type checker (tsc --noEmit, mypy, etc.)
   - Run all tests (not just the ones you think are relevant)
   - Manually verify the specific flows that use this code
   - Check that nothing else broke (run full test suite)
```

