## Removing Old / Legacy Code

### When to Remove

- Feature is no longer used (confirmed by stakeholder / documented decision)
- Code is dead (no callers, no references, no imports)
- Dependency is deprecated and replaced
- Temporary workaround / hack whose issue is now fixed
- Feature flag that's been 100% enabled for a full release cycle (remove the flag, keep the code). Kill-switch flags for critical features may stay longer.
- A/B test that's been decided (remove the losing variant)

### Removal Checklist

```
1. CONFIRM it's truly unused
   - Search the ENTIRE codebase for references (function name, class name, file imports)
   - Search for string references (API paths, route names, event names)
   - Check if it's used dynamically (string interpolation building function names)
   - Check if external systems call it (other services, cron jobs, webhooks)
   - Check if it's referenced in configuration files, env vars, or documentation

2. REMOVE completely
   - Delete the code file (or remove the specific function/component)
   - Delete associated tests
   - Delete associated types/interfaces (if only used by the removed code)
   - Remove from exports / barrel files (index.ts)
   - Remove from route registrations
   - Remove from navigation menus
   - Remove unused imports in files that referenced it
   - Remove unused dependencies (npm packages, pip packages) if this was the only consumer

3. VERIFY nothing broke
   - Run type checker - catches missing imports/references
   - Run linter - catches unused imports
   - Run all tests - catches broken functionality
   - Build the project - catches compilation errors
   - Do a quick smoke test of related features

4. DOCUMENT the removal
   - Commit message explains WHY it was removed (not just "removed old code")
   - Update CHANGELOG.md
   - Update any documentation that referenced the removed feature
```

### Rules

- **Never comment out code** as a way to "remove" it - delete it. Git has the history.
- **Remove in a dedicated PR** - don't mix removal with new feature work
- **Keep removals focused** - a cleanup PR can batch related removals, but don't mix removals with new features in the same PR
- **If unsure, add a deprecation warning first** - log a warning for 2 weeks, then remove if no hits

