## Code Consistency Enforcement

### How to Ensure Every Developer Produces Identical Code

```
1. AUTOMATED ENFORCEMENT (catches 80% of issues)
   - Linter configured with project rules (ESLint, Ruff, etc.)
   - Formatter auto-runs on save and pre-commit (Prettier, Black, etc.)
   - Type checker in CI (tsc --noEmit, mypy --strict)
   - Import order enforced by linter rule
   - File length limits enforced by linter rule
   - Naming convention checked by linter rule (where available)

2. PR REVIEW CHECKLIST (catches the other 20%)
   Every PR reviewer checks:
   - [ ] Function anatomy follows the pattern (guards -> logic -> return)
   - [ ] Component anatomy follows the pattern (hooks -> handlers -> early returns -> render)
   - [ ] API handler follows the 7-step pattern
   - [ ] No non-idiomatic abbreviations in names (see naming.md)
   - [ ] No magic numbers (all extracted to constants)
   - [ ] No duplicate logic (uses existing utilities)
   - [ ] Error handling is complete (not just happy path)
   - [ ] Types are explicit on exported functions
   - [ ] Tests exist for new logic
   - [ ] No console.log or debug artifacts

3. NEW CONTRIBUTOR SETUP (prevents issues from day 1)
   - New developer reads rules/ folder before writing any code
   - First PR is reviewed against the full checklist (teaching moment)
   - Pair on the second PR if first had many pattern violations
   - After 3 PRs following the patterns, developer is autonomous

4. PERIODIC ALIGNMENT (prevents drift over time)
   - Monthly: spot-check 3 random files from each developer for pattern compliance
   - If patterns are drifting: team discussion about which pattern to follow
   - Update rules/ if the team agrees on a better pattern (don't just drift - decide and document)
```

