## Refactoring Rules

### When to Refactor

- Before adding a new feature to a messy area (clean first, then build)
- When you see the same code copied in 3+ places (extract to shared utility)
- When a file exceeds size limits (split into smaller modules)
- When a function exceeds 50 lines (see code-formatting.md - consider extracting helper functions)
- When tests are hard to write (usually means the code is too tightly coupled)

### When NOT to Refactor

- During a production hotfix (fix the bug, refactor later)
- When you don't have tests for the area (add tests first, then refactor)
- When the code is about to be replaced (don't polish what you're deleting)
- When it's purely stylistic and the current code works fine (don't churn for no value)

### Refactoring Checklist

```
1. Ensure tests exist for the code being refactored (add them first if they don't)
2. Make the change in small, verifiable steps
3. Run tests after EACH step (not just at the end)
4. Don't change behavior - refactoring means same inputs -> same outputs
5. If behavior needs to change, that's a separate PR (refactor first, then change behavior)
6. Update all callers in the same PR (don't leave broken references)
7. Commit message starts with "refactor:" and explains WHY
```

